<font color="#FF0000">COMMENT TO LIEN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19 23:28:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
&gt;&quot;I am a 22 year-old Vietnamese refugee/US citizen in graduate school, doing work on Vietnamese re-membering practices about the war. I'm curious, however, about attitudes toward U.S. Vietnamese among veterans and non-veterans alike. If Vietnam is a bad memory, what are we?&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Lein,<br><br>
The Vietnam War was a situation, a very bad situation for all involved.<br><br>
The Vietnamese People are just simply people, fellow humans who, despite cultural wellspring differences, live and feel like me, like everyone else. We are all good, bad, indifferent, biased, sad, happy, and everything in between.<br><br>
There are those with whom I am at philosophical odds of any nationality, race, and all the other things we use to characterize one another. Those odds are a quality of thought, not looks or situation, or characterization.<br><br>
I once had a marvelous discussion with a Vietnamese man who was very young when I was in country, and he remembered the war. He said he understood that I had been a Vietnam Veteran. I countered by saying that I am a Vietnam Veteran.<br>
We shared the pain in our eyes, and parted as we met, as friends.<br><br>
Those are my feelings and thoughts. <br><br>
Arthur  <br>

